# Paper Summary: Measuring Progress on Scalable Oversight for Large Language Models

**Title:** "Measuring Progress on Scalable Oversight for Large Language Models"

**Authors:** Samuel R. Bowman, Jeeyoon Hyun, Ethan Perez, Edwin Chen, Craig Pettit, Scott Heiner, and 39 additional co-authors (46 total from Anthropic and collaborating institutions)

**Abstract Overview:**
The researchers address the challenge of "supervising systems that potentially outperform us on most skills relevant to the task at hand." They propose an experimental framework using tasks where human specialists succeed but general AI systems fail. Testing on MMLU and time-limited QuALITY tasks, they found that "human participants who interact with an unreliable large-language-model dialog assistant through chat...substantially outperform both the model alone and their own unaided performance."

**Key Topics:**
- Scalable oversight of AI systems
- Human-AI collaboration and interaction
- Large language model evaluation
- AI safety and alignment
- Human-computer interaction design
- Question-answering task performance
- Empirical AI safety research

**Submission Details:** Submitted November 4, 2022; revised November 11, 2022 (arXiv:2211.03540)

