The search results provide comprehensive information about responsible scaling policies and dangerous capability evaluations for frontier AI models in 2025-2026:

## Key Frameworks and Policies

Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy, Google DeepMind's Frontier Safety Framework, and OpenAI's Preparedness Framework (all updated in 2025) adopt broadly similar, misuse-focused approaches to monitoring dangerous capabilities (bio/chem, cyber, and AI self-improvement).

## Responsible Scaling Policy Version 3.0

Anthropic defines a "highly capable" model as one that could fully automate or dramatically accelerate the work of large research teams in domains threatening international security. Currently, evaluations focus specifically on AI R&D, where a model would be considered highly capable if it could compress two years of 2018-2024 AI progress into a single year.

Anthropic's Version 3.0 is a comprehensive rewrite involving the publication of Frontier Safety Roadmaps with detailed safety goals, and Risk Reports that quantify risk across all deployed models. Risk Reports will be published online (with some redactions) every 3-6 months.

## Dangerous Capability Evaluations

Most policies outline dangerous capability thresholds which are compared to the results of model evaluations to determine whether they have been crossed. These evaluations typically focus on risks of misuse by external actors in concerning domains, such as biorisk, cyber offense, persuasion, or those arising from model autonomy.

## Industry Adoption

Within a few months of Anthropic announcing its RSP, both OpenAI and Google DeepMind adopted broadly similar frameworks, and some companies have also implemented bioweapon-related classifiers in a similar vein to Anthropic's ASL-3 defenses.


