Ryan Greenblatt and Vivek Hebbar have conducted research examining how training a model changes its goals (June 2025), and Redwood Research is interested in techniques that catch scheming AIs as well as techniques for eliciting high-quality work from schemers, particularly important when AIs can subtly sabotage.

Research on how to solve diffuse threats like research sabotage with AI control exists, addressing threat models where catastrophe requires numerous failures, but each failure is only weak evidence of malign intent when investigated.

## Control Evaluations Framework

Buck Shlegeris and Ryan Greenblatt originally motivated control evaluations as a way to mitigate risks from 'scheming' AI models: models that consistently pursue power-seeking goals in a covert way. In this framing, a control evaluation is a way to upper bound P(Unacceptable outcomes occur | AI models are scheming), and traditional control evaluations involve estimating scheming probabilities.

## Recent Publications

Recent work includes evaluating control protocols for untrusted AI agents (2025), and earlier work titled "AI Control: Improving Safety Despite Intentional Subversion" by Ryan Greenblatt, Buck Shlegeris and colleagues was published at ICML 2024.


